player.seasonOutlook: After elbow surgery cut his 2017 season short, Matz rebounded to make 30 starts for the first time in his career. The southpaw finished with a 3.97 ERA and 1.25 WHIP while throwing a personal-best 154 innings. Matz saw an uptick in the average velocity of his slider, resulting in a career-best 8.9 K/9. It wasn't all good for the 27-year-old, however, as he walked too many batters (career-worst 3.4 BB/9) and served up too many homers (1.5 HR/9), leading to a 4.62 FIP. He also struggled early in games, posting a 7.28 ERA in the first inning. Matz missed time in August with an elbow issue, but he proved his health with a 2.51 ERA and 10.9 K/9 in September. While Matz carries some intrigue, he still comes with plenty of risk given his injury history.

Odorizzi, who was dealt from Tampa Bay to Minnesota prior to the 2018 campaign, was unspectacular in his first year with the Twins. Despite improving both his strikeout (8.9 K/9) and home run (1.1 HR/9) rates from 2017 (8.0 K/9, 1.9 HR/9), the right-hander finished the season with seven wins and a lackluster 4.49 ERA and 1.35 WHIP -- all career-worst marks over a full season. Odorizzi's struggles can largely be attributed to his inability to work through the order a third time. While he kept a tidy 3.04 ERA the first two times through the order last season, that number more than tripled (11.44 ERA) his third time through. Odorizzi has made at least 28 starts in five straight seasons and appears safe in the Twins' rotation, but his innings total could fall with better utilization.

Lopez's shine has all but worn off after a pair of mediocre showings in his first two shots at the big leagues. But the young righty finished 2018 exceedingly well and the campaign as a whole, at least on the surface, appears to be a real step forward. In his first full season in the rotation, his ERA dropped to 3.91, nearly a full run lower than the 4.81 mark he had coming into the season. Digging beneath the surface shows a less flattering picture. His 4.63 FIP was slightly above his 4.35 FIP from his first two seasons, the product of a middling 18.9 percent strikeout rate and 9.4 percent walk rate. His career 1.16 HR/9 is around league average, but that's been due more to HR/FB rate luck than an ability to induce groundballs. A step back there would leave Lopez as a back-end starter.

Anderson started Opening Day for the Brewers last season and pitched like an ace that day, but things went downhill after that as he rarely went deep into games and served up long balls left and right. Anderson was a top-notch starter from the second half of 2016 through the end of 2017, but his fastball was far less effective last season, which resulted in a jump in his ERA of over a run. Things could have been even worse for him, as he finished 2018 with a FIP of 5.22. While he entered last season as the Brewers' top starter, he finished it out of the rotation, and off the playoff roster. Anderson signed a multi-year deal in 2017, so the Brewers will no doubt give him a chance to reclaim his place in the rotation during spring training. However, it's far from a guarantee he breaks camp with a spot, and even if he does, he's going to have to rediscover his fastball to find the same success he enjoyed in the past.

Minor returned to the rotation for the first time since 2014 with good results, posting a 4.18 ERA in 28 starts, a number which looks considerably better when considering his tough home park. He couldn't keep up the strong 28.7 percent strikeout rate he posted in the Royals' bullpen the season before, but that was to be expected. His 20.6 percent mark last season wasn't great but wasn't far below league average. Combined with good control (5.9 percent walk rate), he looks like a useful major-league starter. The lefty has some fantasy appeal, especially in deeper formats, though the homer trouble at home last season (1.91 HR/9) leaves him as more of a road streamer. A poor roster overall hurts his chances at wins while his injury history lowers the floor considerably.

Can a pitcher who will be 31 years old on Opening Day and who owns a career ERA north of 4.00 to be considered promising? If so, that pitcher is Cahill. Few pitchers combine strikeouts with ground balls as well he does. His 53.4 percent ground ball rate ranked seventh among all pitchers who threw at least 110 innings last season, sandwiched between Dallas Keuchel and Jake Arrieta, and only one pitcher above him (Lance McCullers Jr.) outdid his 22.2 percent strikeout rate. He also trimmed his walk rate to a respectable 9.1 percent. That combination of skills could be overlooked at draft time since it's attached to a player with a reputation as mediocre as Cahill's. Injury concerns help keep the hype down, as he hasn't thrown more than 110.2 innings since 2013, but he has real sleeper potential if his skills and health hold up this season.

Anderson could be a moderately interesting fantasy option if he pitched for a different team. His 22.3 percent strikeout rate last season exactly matched the league average, while his 8.0 percent walk rate was a hair better, giving him a solid ERA- of 98. At Coors Field, however, being a touch better than average translates to a 4.55 ERA, making him a rather unappealing candidate. His respectable skill set should theoretically make him a good streaming option, playable in weeks where he only starts in easier parks, but he's oddly had a lower ERA at home than on the road in each of his three seasons. Pitches do move differently in the thin Colorado air, so it's possible that he's gotten used to pitching at home, but it's easy to see that trend reversing this season, especially as his ground ball rate has decreased for three straight seasons.

Kelly brought the heat (98.7 mph average fastball) in 2018, but his results weren't overly impressive. His 12.6 K-BB percent ranked 67th among 89 relievers that tossed at least 60 frames, while his surface numbers (4.39 ERA, 1.36 WHIP) were similarly mediocre. Kelly raised his performance when it mattered most, conceding just one run while striking out 13 over 11.1 postseason frames to help the Red Sox take the World Series. After inking a three-year, $25 million contract with the Dodgers this winter, Kelly now steps in as one Kenley Jansen's top setup men.

Roark is primarily an innings eater at stage of his career, but he still represented a significant upgrade for the Reds -- his 4.34 ERA last season was better than their staff's 4.65 mark. He should have a steady role in a starting rotation that can use all the stability it can get, and that locked-in role should give him deep-league value. Downgrades in team quality and home park combined with age and a diminishing ground ball rate make him a risk in shallower formats, however. The 32-year-old showed good control with a 6.6 percent walk rate last season, but that was paired with a drop in strikeouts (to 19.2 percent). If he can get the groundball rate back to around 48 percent, where it was the three seasons prior to 2018, that would help in a big way at Great American Ball Park.

Junis didn't do anything exciting last season, but he was one of the best arms on the Royals' staff. His underlying numbers back up his ERA, as Junis paired a 21.6 percent strikeout rate with a low 5.7 percent walk rate. He had a ground ball rate not far below the league average, but even so the right-hander had major homer trouble, and those problems were especially bad at home (1.97 HR/9). The long ball is usually an issue for fastball/slider pitchers who pound the zone. He's leaned on the (very good) slider, throwing it 39.3 percent of the time last season, but his 91.1 mph fastball has been hit around and he doesn't appear to trust his changeup, using it just 5.9 percent of the time. His is very much a back-end starter profile, and it doesn't seem particularly likely that Junis is about to become anything more than that. He does have plenty of job security pitching for Kansas City.

Injuries limited Wacha yet again in 2018, with an oblique issue shutting him down for the season in June. In 15 starts prior to the injury, he posted a strong 3.20 ERA, looking on the surface like he was back to his younger self. Digging a little deeper gives reason for some concern, though, as his 4.22 FIP (the worst mark of his six-year career) was average at best. His mediocre 20.0 percent strikeout rate was right in line with his career numbers, but his walk rate jumped to 10.1 percent after sitting below 8 percent in each of his previous five seasons. A friendly home park and a solid track record keep Wacha interesting, but the injury risk and regression risk are both significant, limiting his appeal.

After a promising start to his career in Oakland, Gray has stalled out in recent seasons, posting a 4.90 ERA in 130.1 innings for the Yankees last season and losing his spot in the rotation. He'll look to turn things around with the Reds in 2019. From a fantasy perspective, the move trades one tough park for another, but a guaranteed rotation spot and a reunion with old pitching coach Derek Johnson make the move nevertheless a clear plus. He's a legitimate bounce-back candidate, as his underlying numbers weren't all that bad, and he was actually quite good on the road. His 21.1 percent strikeout rate and 9.8 percent walk rate were each worse than average, but not by much, and when combined with a 50.0 percent ground ball rate, he looks like a fine middle-of-the-rotation starter.

Shoulder issues limited Duffy to 28 starts last season and he didn't look anything like himself when available, finishing the year with a 4.88 ERA, the highest mark since his rookie campaign. His underlying stats don't provide any reason for optimism, as he was worse than average in strikeout rate (20.4 percent), walk rate (10.1 percent) and groundball rate (35.4 percent). A 30-year-old pitcher with injury concerns and clear signs of decline is understandably one whose fantasy stock will fall quite far. He could at least be worth a flier if his price drops far enough, as he recorded a 3.47 ERA over the previous four seasons, and he pitches in a friendly home park. Managers may be forced to cut bait if his injury issues linger, but Duffy has more upside than many other pitchers drafted in his range.

Sanchez's ERAs from 2013 to 2017 told the story of a pitcher whose age was catching up to him and who would soon be out of the league: 2.75, 3.43, 4.99, 5.87, 6.41. As a 34-year-old in 2018, a new cutter (used at the expense of his four-seamer) and an improved changeup reversed that trend, as he posted the same 2.83 ERA he posted as a rookie back in 2006. The performance doesn't seem like a fluke, as his strikeout rate jumped to 24.4 percent while his walk rate remained fairly low at 7.6 percent. His 3.62 FIP suggests that he overachieved a bit but was still a capable pitcher. The Nationals believed in his rebound, handing him a two-year contract. Sanchez hasn't been the most durable, making fewer than 30 starts in each season since 2012, but the new and improved Sanchez should remain a viable option when available.

The 31-year-old Leake is a viable major-league starter, but an ultra-low strikeout rate leaves him as a largely unappealing option for traditional rotisserie leagues. He has been a slightly-better-than-average starter in real life in each of the last three seasons, with his FIP ranging from 3.83 to 4.14 in that time. His success stems largely from being stingy with free passes (4.3 percent walk rate in 2018) and keeping the ball on the ground. His ground ball rate fell five percentage points last season, but it was still above average at 48.7 percent. Leake threw his changeup more than ever in 2018 and ended up with the best chase rate of his career, but that didn't translate to more strikeouts, as his 15.2 percent strikeout rate was his lowest since 2013. Leake has significantly more appeal in points leagues and AL-only formats where volume and stability are emphasized to a greater degree.

Urena has quietly put together two strong seasons for the Marlins, and in 2018 the peripherals were more supportive of the results. He upped his groundball rate to a career-high 49.6 percent and in turn dropped his home run rate to 0.98 HR/9. The right-hander cut his walk rate and raised his strikeout rate by nearly three percentage points, as well. Urena's strikeouts were still below average at 18.3 perent, but there's some reason for hope that he can take another step forward at age 27, namely an above-average 31.7 percent chase rate and the fact that he averages 95 mph with his fastball. Urena's third pitch -- the changeup -- trails the rest of his arsenal and the team context isn't great, but Urena is getting no respect for what he did last season, and at a late-round cost, it's not a bad dart throw.

If you're digging around in the bargain bin for a starting pitcher and considering Nova, know this: He has posted an ERA over 5.00 on the road in each of the past three seasons and no longer has the park advantage following an offseason trade to the White Sox. He was a sub-3.00 ERA pitcher last season at PNC Park -- a top-five park for pitchers -- but a diminishing ground ball rate led to major homer trouble away from home (2.03 HR/9). Guaranteed Rate Field in Chicago played more neutral last season, but it's still a significant downgrade for Nova. He regularly ranks among the league leaders in walk rate, but Nova's strikeout rate sat at 16.7 percent the last two seasons -- well below average -- and all that contact leaves a lot up to chance from start to start. At least he will probably get to make a few starts against the Tigers and Royals.

Few would have expected Miley to be a top-two starter on a team that reached the NLCS last season, but that's precisely what happened, as Miley came out of nowhere to have his best season since 2015. Miley earned a spot in the rotation during spring training, but an oblique injury delayed the start of his season until May. Once Miley made his debut, he made 16 starts for the Brewers and did not allow more than three earned runs in any of them. The key to Miley's success last year was not added velocity -- his average fastball was right in line with his career average -- but rather a new pitch mix that saw him feature his cutter and offspeed stuff. Despite the big 2018 campaign, Miley earned only a one-year contract from the Astros during the offseason. His pitch mix sets him up for more success, and his new team will certainly help in his quest to pick up wins. However, some regression should be factored in, as Miley's FIP (3.59) was more than a run higher than the ERA he finished with in 2018.
